{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_graham_ver01/data/sn87062268/00415662786/1914010501/0083.xml":{"full_text":"THE PENSACOLA JOURNAL, MONDAY MORNING, J ANUARY 5, 1914.\nDAILY, WEEKLY, SUNDAY,\nBY\nJOURNAL PUBLISHING COMPANY.\nFRANK L. MAYES, President.\nMEMBER THE ASSOCIATED PRESS.\nSUBSCRIPTION HATES:\nOn Wm1c. Dallv and Slindav .13\nTw wb- rtaiiv and Sunday .25\nOne Month Dally and Sunday fB\nThree Mnth. Dally and Sunday. 1.\"\nSix Months. Dally and Sunday 3.25\nOn Year. Dattv and Sunday 6.30\nSunday Only, One Year\nWeekly Journal. One Year\n1.00\nOffice Joi'rnal Pulldtng, Comer De\nLuna and Intrndencta.\nEntered econd-elaaa matter at\nthe poetoWre at Pen-ola. Flo-'da,\nunder Act of Congress, March 3, 1879.\nPhonies Editorial Rpoma, 38.\nnees Offee, 1500.\nBusl-\nFOREIGN ADVERTISING.\nForeign Advertising: Robert MacQuold,\nSpecial Representative.\nNew York Office; Room 903, Bruna\nWlrk Bulldlno.\nChicago Office: Advertising Building.\nRepresentative Bartholdt\nIs Going To Retire.\nRepresentative Bartholdt of the\nTenth Missouri congressional district\nannounces that he will not be a can\ndidate for re-election.\nThis announcement is the most sen\nsible and satisfactory thins that the\nMissouri congressman has recently\ndone. His only service in congress has\nbeen In behalf of the breweries and\nthe special interests and his retirement\nshould have been an enforced one long\nago.\nGradually but surely the reactionary\nrepresentatives are being: relegated to\nthe rear. The Washington atmosphere\nis no longer congenial to them, and\nthe home folks on the other hand are\nfat finding them out. The fact that\nBartholdt Is not going to wait to be\nPLAYGROUNDS\nMOVEMENT IS A\nPOPULAR ONE\nANNUAL CENSUS WHICH HAS\nJUST BEEN TAKEN SHOWS EX\nTENT TO WHICH SAME HAS\nSPREAD IN LATE YEARS.\ni\ndefeated, but retires voluntarily, is al- j\nmost the only thing that stands to his j\ncredit as a congressman.\nMONDAY, JANUARY 8, 1914.\nMay This Year Be\nThe Best Year.\nWith every rising of the sun\nThink of your life as Just begun.\nThe Past has canceled and buried deep\nAll yesterdays. There let them sleep.\nConcern yourself with but Today.\nGrasp It, and teach It to obey\nTour will and plan. Since time began\nToday has been the friend of man.\nTon And Today! A soul rnbllme\nAnd the great heritage of time.\nWith God himself to bind the twain.\nGo forth, brave heart: Attain! Attain!\nAnon, from British Weekly.\nXothtng that Is worth doing is easy\nIt Is not easy to build a house, or to\nestablish an Industry, or to found a\ncity. But it is possible to do all these\nthings, with work.\nPensaoola is facing a new era today.\nThe year Just past has been one of\nmany vicissitudes and changes, and the\ncity has passed, with other sections of\nthe country, through a number of\ncrises.\nBut the year Is past. The year that\nla before us may be productive of much\ngood, and the results attained may be\nwonderful and far reaching, if every\nbody works together for the common\ngood.\nEvery bit of success that comes to\none person In Pensacola helps another\nperson. Man cannot live to himself\nIt Is Just as Impossible as for the sun\nto shine without others feeling the re\nflected brightness.\nWe can make this year in Pensaco\nla's history a wonderful year, a good\nyear and a worth while year, but to do\nthis, we must all work together for the\ncommon good.\nThe conditions that have made the\npast year a hard one In many ways\nare changed to a greater or less degree\nall over the country.\nThe new tariff law and the currency\nlaw. Just passed, will do much toward\nsettling .conditions that have been\nsomewhat turoulent. Locally, the out\nlook Is brightening. The naval stores\nbusiness, which was threatened disas\ntrously early In the year 1913, Is again\nassuming a normal tone.\nIn spite of business depression every\nwhere, the city has enjoyed a continu\nous building campaign.\nThe magnificent new depot, the fine\nhotel, and the attention that has been\ndirected to Pensacola as a harbor, and\nto the Pensacola navy yard, has done\nmuch to advertise Pensacola to the\nworld.\nPensacola haa wonderful natural ad\nvantages, j\nThis Is so true as to iiave become\naxiomatic.\nPensacola has men and plenty of\nthem to embrace these advantages. Let\nus all do what we can. even if it is but\nlittle, to advance Pensacola's Interests\nduring the year that is now ours.\nL pnniwR IK\nVH LUUilVU IfliUU\nHAYWARD AID\nA. P. HOWARD\nCEREMONY OCCURRED SATUR\nDAY NIGHT IN NEW ORLEANS\nAND WAS ONE OF THE REAL\nSOCIAL EVENTS OF THE SEASON.\nHard Times At the\nWashington Hotels.\nThere Is at least one class of people\nIn one city to whom the Wilson ad\nministration has brought hard times.\nThose are the hotel people in Wash\nington. Since time immemorial, the big profits\nreaped by the Washington hotels have\ncome from the lobby, whose members\nat all times flocked to the national cap\nital to Influence legislation and cor\nrupt legislators. The St. Louis Post\nDispatch thus describes the painful sit\nuation as It now exists in Washing\nton: The subjugation of the lobbv Is so\ncomplete that Washington hotel pro\nprietors complain of poor business, said\nex-uov. Folk while on a visit to St\nLouis. This Is a sign of temporary\nbusiness depression in which the\"public\nwill take great satisfaction. The loss\nto the hotel keepers from the rout of\ntne insidious lobby which used to lodge\niiseii in cosuy suites and spend mo\nney lavishly In the cafes is the peo\nple's gain.\nIf tne lobby representatives are no\nlonger m evidence in the hotel corri\ndors and are \"paged\" in vain in the\npalm room, they must, indeed, have\nvanished. The average citizen's New\nYear wish for Washington hotel keep\ners is that they may have much pros\nperity in the future, but that the dis\nappearance of one important source of\nprosperity in the past may be perma\nnent. The example at Washington under\nPresident Wilson's administration Is\none that may well be followed by state\nadministrations everywhere. The lob\nby and the lobbyist have no place in\naa honest government.\nConcerning the wedding of a young\nlady who has relatives hero and who\nha3 visited this city frequently, th\nXew Orleans Times-Democrat of Sun\nday printed the following:\nMembers of the fashionable world hero\ncrowded St. Paul's Episcopal church\nlast. evening tor the wedding of Miss\nLaura Hayward. daughter of Mr. and\nMrs. James D. Hayward, to Mr. Alviu\nP. Howard, which was a brilliant event\nof the winter socially, and one of the\nmost interesting nuptials ol\" recent\ndate. Both families are among the h:-st\nknown and most prominent in smart\ncircles In Xew Orleans, and the wed\nding in consequence has come in for\nan extra share of social attention.\nMiss Hayward is the youngest ot sev\neral sisters, all of whom have been\nbelles in society here, and since the\nwinter of her debut, two years\nhas enjoyed unusual popularity. Mr.\nHoward, a son of the late Frank T.\nHoward of New Orleans, ard is prom\ninent in club and social circles of the\ncity.\nThe ceremony took place at S 'clock\nin the midst of much beauty, the dec\norations of the church being very elab\norate and rich, and carried out with\nralms and ferns, and the greatest pro\nfusion of Easter lilies. Arches were\narranged across the center aisle at in\ntervals, down the length of the church,\nand were caught to the pews with\nclusters of Easter lilies, tied with white\nsash ribbon. The march from \"Tann\nhauser\" was played as the bridal\nparty entered, led by thn ushers,\nMessrs. Atwood L. Rice, John P. La\nbouisse. Harrison B. Smith of Cincin\nati and Louis Howard. The grooms\nmen were Messrs. Arthur Gardner of\nXew York, Jack Howard. Lucien E.\nLyons, Jr., and William Bell.\nThe bride has as her attendants, her\nsisters, Mrs. Atwood L. Rice, Mrs.\nJohn P. Labouisse and Mrs. J. I. Lit\ntle, and as bridesmaids Misses Flores\nHoward and Leola Stantor, Her four\nlittle nieces Misses Lucile, Stella, Jane\nand Sedley Hayward, acted as flower\ngirls, wearing beautiful frocks in white\nshadow lace over pink, with trlmmnigs\nof tiny pink roses, and carrying bas\nkets filled with pink roses and lilies\nof the valley, attached from one to\nthe other by garlands of asparagus\nfern and sprays of lilies of lite vall-y.\nThe bride's attendant wore an es\npecially beautiful gown sfcnilar in de\nsign and color, and were of pale pink\ncharmeuse and tulle, with short tunics\nembroidered in crystals. They car\nried old-fashioned bouquets of rink\nroses, lilies of the valley and while\nlilacs. The bride entered with her\nfather, looking unusually lovely in a I\nrich bridal dress of white satin, with j\nan oversKirt ana ooaice or exqms.te\nold point lace, one of the loveliest worn\nrecently. Her veil was of similar lace,\nfalling to the end of the long court\ntrain, and she carried white orchids\nand lilies of the valley. Ofhicating at\nthe ceremony was Rev. Dr. John La\nMothe. Mr. Edgar Howard of Xew Or\nleans and Philadelphia, arid a brother\nof the bridegroom, was the bes- man.\nThere was lovely music during the\nsigning of the register, am' as the\nbridal rarty left the church.\nA beautiful wedding reception, with\na large number of guests attending,\nfollowed the ceremony at the home of\nMr. \"and Mrs. Hayward. in First street. J\nMrs. Hayward wearing a, nanasome\ngown of white charmeuse, with a tunic\nof lace, assisted In receiving by Mrs.\nHarry T. Howard and the members of\nthe bridal party. The drawing room\nand other reception rooms of the home\nwere exquisitely decorated with a mass\nof white lilacs and lilies of the valley.\nThe bride and bridegroom received the\nrnests under an arch- of dainty ferns,\nlilacs and lilies of the valley, tied with\nlarge bows of white tulle. In the din\ning room, where the bridal cake was\ncut. the color scheme was in green\nand white. A large silver plateau in\nthe center of the table held white roses\nand lilies of the valley, and the lights\nwer shadd in pale green Eilk with\ncrystals;.\nMr. Howard and his bride will sail\nfrom Xew York Jan. 10. on their way\nto Egypt, going by the way of the\nMediterranean. They will lie absent\nuntil some time in March, and on their\nreturn to Xew Orleans will be at home\nat the Howard residence facing La\nfayette Square.\nAmong the out-of-town guests here\nfor the wedding were: Mr. Wilmer\nHayward, a brother of the bride: Dr.\nClarence Hutchinson and Mr. Dariel\nMcMillan, all of Pensacola. m Fla.; Mr.\nand Mrs. Edgar Howard, Mrs. Xewhall\nand Miss Rebecca Xewhall of Chestnut\nHill. Pa.: Mr. Arthur Gardner of Xew\nYork ard Mr. Harrison B. Smith of\nCincinnati.\nThere will be a wonderful array of\nbeautiful gifts sent to the young couple\nby friends from here and various parts\nof the country.\nported In twenty cities to the toUl of\n$2,353,000. The report shows that chil\ndren In seventy cities have been given\nnew playgrounds during the past year.\nThe cities which became converts to\nthe movement in the previous year had\nnumbered only 43.\nPlay leaders appear to be now pro\nfessionally recognized the country over.\nTwenty-four hundred playgrounds and\nrecreation centers are under regular\npaid supervision and more than 6,000\nnersons are making It their profession\nto serve as leaders of play and general\nrecreation. It is an enlistment of a\nthousand new workers in this line dur\ning the past year, and efficiency iw so\ngenerally demanded of these leaders\nthat training classes for them are be\n'ng maintained, and in 35 of these\neentei's 2.63S students are reported.\nLeadership Is Thing Needed.\nLeadership is regarded as the crux of\nthe playsrround and recreation move\nment. AlmoEt invariably the commu\nnities which have reported failure in\nl tne wor tney started have explainea\nit by the report that they had no lead\nBY ASSOCIATED PREisS. ership. The point is becoming so gen-\nXcw York, Jan. 5. The business of eraJly appreciated that the plAyground